Fires in the Paran√° River Delta

Natalia Morandeira

8/7/2020

Wildfires can be monitored and analyzed using thermal hotspots records derived from satellite data. In 2020, the Paran√° River floodplain (Argentina) is suffering from a severe drought, and thousands of hotspots ‚Äîprobably active fires‚Äî are daily reported by the Fire Information for Resource Management System (FIRMS-NASA). FIRMS-NASA products are provided in several spatial objects (shapefiles): recent and archive records from several sensors. I aimed to handle these data, analyze the number of hotspots during 2020, and compare the disaster with previous years‚Äô situation. Using sp, tidyverse, spdplyr, ggplot2 and RMarkDown, I obtain reproducible reports. My workflow can be used to analyze hotspot data in any other interest area.

This script is authored by Natalia Morandeira. The data analysis and plots were included in several publications that aimed to spread what is happening in the Paran√° River Delta, and also on periodistic interviews. Some of the articles were written by Patricia Kandus, Natalia Morandeira and Priscilla Minotti (Instituto de Investigaci√≥n e Ingenier√≠a Ambiental, Universidad Nacional de San Mart√≠n, Buenos Aires, Argentina).

Some links of periodistic articles which use the information here :

  • [‚ÄúEl Delta en llamas‚Äù (translated, ‚ÄúDelta on fire‚Äù)]{http://www.unsam.edu.ar/tss/el-delta-en-llamas/}, published by Agencia TSS
  • Twitter thread of the Universidad Nacional de San Mart√≠n
  • ‚ÄúEl Delta no es una mercanc√≠a‚Äù (translated, ‚ÄúThe Delta is not a mercancy‚Äù), published by Hamartia.

Data source

  • Paran√° River Delta limits: shapefile of the study area
  • Hotspots from FIRMS-NASA, https://firms.modaps.eosdis.nasa.gov/map/#t:adv;d:2020-07-28..2020-08-03;@-59.9,-33.1,8z

Naming conventions of the FIRMS data:

  • DL_FIRE_M6.xx if you requested MODIS data (M6 stands for MODIS Collection 6), or
  • DL_FIRE_V1.xx if you requested VIIRS 375m data from S-NPP
  • DL_FIRE_J1.xx if you requested VIIRS 375m data from NOAA-20(JPSS-1)

Spatial data pre-processing

  1. Read files and unzip
  2. Handle the files as spatial data
  3. Merge
  4. Re-project
  5. Clip by study area

To read and unzip, we first set the names of the two ZIP files, one from MODIS and the other from VIIRS satellites. Each of these zips has two shapefiles: recent and archive records.

zip_hotspots_VIIRS <- "data/zip/DL_FIRE_V1_143928.zip"
zip_hotspots_MODIS <- "data/zip/DL_FIRE_M6_143927.zip"

unzip(zip_hotspots_VIIRS, exdir = "data/hotspots/") 
unzip(zip_hotspots_MODIS, exdir = "data/hotspots/")

focos_cum <- focos2020 %>%

  group_by(acq_date) %>%

p <- focos_cum %>%
  pivot_longer(names_to = "focos", values_to = "cantidad", col=cantidad_diaria:acumulado) %>%
  ggplot(aes (x=acq_date, y=cantidad, color=focos)) +
  annotation_custom(rasterGrob(img, width = unit(1,"npc"), height = unit(1,"npc")), 
                    -Inf, Inf, -Inf, Inf) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("red", "yellow"),  labels = c("Focos acumulados", "Nuevos focos")) +
  xlab("Fecha") +
  ylab("Cantidad de focos de calor") +
  scale_x_date(date_labels = "%d/%m/%Y", breaks = "week", limits = as.Date(c("2020-01-01", "2020-07-21"))) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(from = 0, to = 4000, by = 500)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45, hjust=1, color="black"), plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0, vjust=1, face = "italic"), plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"), legend.position=c(0.12, 0.85), legend.title = element_blank(), axis.line=element_line(color="black"), axis.text.y=element_text(color="black")) +
  labs(title="Incendios en el Delta del Paran√° (Argentina) durante 2020", subtitle = "Focos de calor por d√≠a y acumulados al 17/06/2020, en base a datos VIIRS de FIRMS-NASA", caption = "Patricia Kandus, Natalia Morandeira y Priscilla Minotti; 3iA-UNSAM. Foto: MAyDS")
